4.4.85 Document   

A Document is a is a logical document that serves as the identifier for a container for some product data.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to a Document: ActivityMethod, Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Document;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  documentTypes : SET[1:?] OF ClassSelect;
  versions : SET[1:?] OF DocumentVersion;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Document.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the Document is known.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Document. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Document. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

documentTypes: the classifications of the Document with respect to specific criteria. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'catalogue': The Document is the catalogue in which the associated object is listed;

    EXAMPLE    The Document can be the catalogue of the manufacturer.

  • 'manual': The Document is the handbook that is supplied for the associated object;
  • 'specification': The Document specifies the considerations that lead to the design finally chosen for the associated object.

versions: the versions of the Document.

4.4.86 DocumentAssignment   

A DocumentAssignment is a mechanism to associate a Document with the objects, where the assigned document provides information about the object it is associated to.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY DocumentAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : ClassSelect;
  assignedDocument : AssignedDocumentSelect;
  assignedTo : SET[1:?] OF DocumentAssignmentSelect;
  documentPortion : OPTIONAL MultiLingualStringSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the DocumentAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: the meaning of the assignment. Where applicable, the following values shall be used:

  • 'additional information': The assigned document provides information that is relevant for the associated object, but is not a description of the associated object itself;
  • 'behaviour': The assigned document specifies information about the behaviour of the associated object;
  • 'description': The assigned document provides textual information for the associated object itself;
  • 'informative': The assigned document may or may not be considered;
  • 'mandatory': The associated object shall conform to the content of the assigned document;
  • 'mathematical description': The assigned document specifies the associated object by providing the algorithmic specification of its behaviour.
  • 'dimensioning standard': The assigned document specifies the dimensioning standard;

    NOTE    The document shall be assigned to a PartView.

    EXAMPLE 2   For a BreakdownElement there is a textual document assigned, explaining the functionality, size, and other characteristics by a DocumentAssignment with role 'description'. Another document, representing the specification of the ProductClass, in which the BreakdownElement is used, is also assigned to the same BreakdownElement by a DocumentAssignment with role 'additional information'.

assignedDocument: the assigned Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, or File.

assignedTo: the objects to which the Document is assigned.

EXAMPLE 1   A document assigned to ActivityAssignment may provide further description of the input or output of that activity.

documentPortion: the word or group of the words that convey the subject or sub contents of the document. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.87 DocumentDefinition   

A DocumentDefinition is one of potentially more alternative representations of a DocumentVersion.

NOTE 1   A DocumentVersion may have more than one representation.

EXAMPLE    A version of a logical document, which contains a shape model, may be represented in the different native formats of two three-dimensional CAD systems.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a DocumentDefinition: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY DocumentDefinition
  ABSTRACT SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (DigitalDocumentDefinition,
                                 PhysicalDocumentDefinition)));
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  documentContent : OPTIONAL ContentProperty;
  documentCreation : OPTIONAL CreationProperty;
  documentFormat : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF FormatProperty;
  documentSize : OPTIONAL SizeProperty;
INVERSE
  viewOf : DocumentVersion FOR views;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the DocumentDefinition.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the DocumentDefinition is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

documentContent: the characteristics of the content of the DocumentDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

documentCreation: further details of the creation of the DocumentDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

documentFormat: the format of the document represented by DocumentDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

documentSize: the size of the document represented by DocumentDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

viewOf: the version of the logical document that is being represented.

4.4.88 DocumentDefinitionRelationship   

A DocumentDefinitionRelationship is a relationship between two DocumentDefinition objects.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to a DocumentDefinitionRelationship: Approval, Effectivity, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY DocumentDefinitionRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : DocumentDefinition;
  related : DocumentDefinition;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the DocumentDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the DocumentDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'addition': The application object specifies that the related document provides supplementary or collateral information with regard to the information provided by the relating document;
  • 'copy': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is a copy of the relating DocumentDefinition;
  • 'decomposition': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is one of potentially more sub documents of the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 1   The decomposition of a document into clauses is an example for the use of this value.

  • 'derivation': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition is derived from the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 2   A raster image may be derived from a three-dimensional CAD model.

    EXAMPLE 3   A html version may be derived from a text document as an alternative.

  • 'peer': The application object specifies that the related document provides required information with regard to that provided by the relating document. The peer document is essential for a complete understanding;
  • 'reference': The application object defines a relationship where the related document is referenced from the relating;

    EXAMPLE 4   A hyperlink is an example for a 'reference'.

  • 'sequence': The application object defines a logical sequence where the related DocumentDefinition comes after the relating DocumentDefinition;

    EXAMPLE 5   A sequence of clauses.

  • 'substitution': The application object defines a relationship where the related DocumentDefinition replaces the relating DocumentDefinition;
  • 'translation': The DocumentDefinitionRelationship specifies that the related document is generated through a translation process from the relating document.

relating: one object of DocumentDefinition that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of DocumentDefinition that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: A DocumentDefinition shall not be related to itself.

4.4.92 DrapedOrientationAngle

NOTE    The warp direction of a fabric shall be placed in the specified direction prior to draping over the part. Once the fabric has been draped, the orientation angle at any given point must be derived from the draped shape of the fabric. The DrapedOrientationAngle will change in the part if the surface of the part has complex curvature.

EXPRESS specification:

*)

  SUBTYPE OF ();
END_ENTITY;

4.4.100 Event   

A Event is the fact of the existence of a state at some point in time.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to an Event: DateTimeString

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Event;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  eventType : ClassSelect;
  actualStartDate : OPTIONAL DateTimeString;
  offset : OPTIONAL Duration;
  plannedStartDate : OPTIONAL DateTimeString;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Event.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Event. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Event. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

eventType: specifies the kind of event.

EXAMPLE    The eventType may be the 'start of production' of a ProductClass specified as 'event context'.

actualStartDate: the actualStartDate specifies the date when the Event actually started. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

offset: specifies the amount of time before or after the defined Event that shall be used to calculate the actual point in time. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

plannedStartDate: the DateTimeString when the Event is or was planned to start. The value of the attribute need not be specified.

4.4.101 EventAssignment   

A EventAssignment is the assignment of an Event to product or activity data.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY EventAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : ClassSelect;
  assignedEvent : Event;

END_ENTITY;

Attribute definitions:

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the EventAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the EventAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: the meaning of the assignment.

EXAMPLE    'Deadline' is an example of role for an event assigned to activities that are expected to be completed before this event.

assignedEvent: the Event to be assigned to product or activity data.

assignedTo: the product or activity data to which the Event is assigned.

4.4.102 EventRelationship   

A EventRelationship is a relationship which exists between two Event objects.

EXAMPLE    An instance of this entity data type with relationType 'sequence' may be used to specify that an event shall end before another event starts.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY EventRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : Event;
  related : Event;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the EventRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the EventRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'actualization': The relationship specifies that the relating Event identifies a predicted or planned event and the related Event identifies the point in time when that event actually occurred. This relationship is valid if the actualStartDate attribute of the relating Event is not specified and the actualStartDate attribute of the related Event is specified, or, if both these attributes are specified and equal;
  • 'exclusiveness': The relationship specifies that the relating and the related Event shall not have any overlap during their duration;
  • 'sequence': The relationship specifies that the relating Event shall be completed before the related Event starts;
  • 'simultaneity': The relationship specifies that both the relating and related Event are considered as occurring during the same time period or shall be performed together in order to ensure consistency and enhance efficiency.

    NOTE    The criteria for 'simultaneity' and in particular the allowed delay between two events declared simultaneous, are user-dependent.

relating: one object of Event that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of Event that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: An shall not be related to itself.

4.4.121 ExternalGeometricModel   

An ExternalGeometricModel is a type of GeometricModel that contains geometry in a three-dimensional context only.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ExternalGeometricModel
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  accuracyType : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  accuracyValue : OPTIONAL REAL;
  definedAs : DigitalFile;
  SELF\GeometricModel.modelElements : SET[1:1] OF CoordinateSystem;
  parameterValues : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF PropertyValue;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

accuracyType: the kind of accuracy that is applied. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'angular accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the maximum value for the absolute angle between two curve tangents or two surface normals for which the creating system assumes curve tangents or surface normals being identical

    NOTE 1   The angular accuracy value can be used to determine the accuracy range for tangent continuous curve or surface connections.

  • 'curvature accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the value for the term under which a system can assume that the two radii of curvature R1 and R2 are identical. The curvature accuracy value is used to determine the accuracy range for curvature continuous curve or surface connections

    NOTE 2   Terms surrounded by the FORMULA symbols represent the absolute values of these terms.

  • 'distance accuracy': A kind of accuracy that specifies the distance under which two points can be considered as having the same location. The distance accuracy value defined for a GeometricModel is valid for all geometric elements of the GeometricModel.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

accuracyValue: a numerical value defining the accuracy of the model. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definedAs: the DigitalFile that contains the externally defined geometry information.

modelElements: the CoordinateSystem that defines the context for the externally described geometry.

parameterValues: the PropertyValue object or group of PropertyValue objects that may be varied in each occurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

A ExternalItem is a

*)

  SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (ExternalRepresentationItem)));

4.4.132 ExternalPropertyDefinition

*)

  UR1: sameAs;

Attribute definitions:

EXAMPLE    A company may accept a mass specified in kilograms or tons, but not in grams or pounds.

A ValueWithUnit of a PropertyValue representing the ExternalPropertyDefinition shall not be expressed with a Unit that is not contained in the allowedUnits, if the allowedUnits is specified. If specified, the unit attribute of ValueWithUnit of a PropertyValue representing the ExternalPropertyDefinition shall be contained in the allowedUnits, if the allowedUnits is specified. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.134 ExternalRepresentationItem   

An ExternalRepresentationItem is a type of ExternalItem whose value is defined in a DigitalFile.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ExternalRepresentationItem
  SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (ExternalCompositeCurveOnSurface,
                        ExternalCurve,
                        ExternalDegeneratePcurve,
                        ExternalLoop,
                        ExternalOrientedSurface,
                        ExternalPcurve,
                        ExternalPointPath,
                        ExternalSurface,
                        ExternalSurfaceCurve)))
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  name : DescriptorSelect;
DERIVE
  SELF\ExternalItem.source : DigitalFile := definedIn.definedAs;
INVERSE
  definedIn : ExternalRepresentation FOR modelElement;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

name: the words or set of words by which the ExternalRepresentationItem is known.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

source: the identification of the DigitalFile that provides the value of the source.

definedIn: the ExternalRepresentation where the ExternalRepresentationItem is defined in.

4.4.143 File   

A File is one of potentially more files on a computer system or in actual stacks of paper that make up a DocumentDefinition.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to an File: ActivityMethod, Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY File
  ABSTRACT SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (DigitalFile,
                                 Hardcopy)));
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  fileType : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  fileContent : OPTIONAL ContentProperty;
  fileCreation : OPTIONAL CreationProperty;
  fileFormat : OPTIONAL FormatProperty;
  fileSize : OPTIONAL SizeProperty;
  locations : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ExternalItem;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileType: the format of the File. It shall only be specified, if the File does not participate in a Document. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileContent: the content of the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileCreation: further details of the context of the creation of the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileFormat: the characteristics of the File that specify the format of the object. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileSize: the characteristics for the size of the File. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

locations: alternatives of the identifier and location of the File.

EXAMPLE    A copy of a document may be found in another department with a different id.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.145 FormatProperty   

A FormatProperty is a specification of characteristics of a File or of a DocumentDefinition that specify the format of the object. At least one of the optional attributes shall be specified for each instance of this object. In the case where a FormatProperty is referred by a DocumentDefinition the characteristics apply to all individual File objects, whereas in the case it is referred by a File the characteristics apply on an individual basis.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY FormatProperty;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  characterCode : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  dataFormat : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  sizeFormat : OPTIONAL RectangularSize;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the FormatProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the FormatProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

characterCode: the character code that is used in the characterized object. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'binary': The document contains data in binary format;
  • 'IEC 61286': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to IEC 61286;
  • 'ISO 646': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO 646;

    NOTE 1   The character set in ISO 646 is identical to the character set commonly known as ASCII

  • 'ISO 6937': The coded character set used to encode the document data is according to ISO/IEC 6937;
  • 'ISO 8859-1': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO 8859-1;

    NOTE 2   The character set in ISO 8859-1 is identical to the character set commonly known as LATIN-1.

  • 'ISO 10646': The coded character set used to encode the document data according to ISO/IEC 10646.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

dataFormat: the convention that was used to structure the information in the characterized object. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'DXF': The document contains data in Drawing Exchange File format;
  • 'IGES': The document contains data in Initial Graphics Exchange Specification format;
  • 'ISO 10303-203': The document contains data in ISO 10303-203 format;
  • 'ISO 10303-214': The document contains data in ISO 10303-214 format;
  • 'TIFF CCITT GR4': The document contains data in TIFF CCITT GR4 format;
  • 'VDAFS': The document contains data in VDAFS format;
  • 'VOXEL': The document contains data in VOXEL format.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

sizeFormat: the dimensions of a physical presentation of the object the sizeFormat is provided for.

EXAMPLE 1   'ISO A0' is an example for the sizeFormat of a drawing that is stored digitally.

EXAMPLE 2   '0.2 x 0.4 x 0.4 meters' is an example for the sizeFormat of a wooden model.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.149 GeneralShapeDependentProperty   

A GeneralShapeDependentProperty is a type of ShapeDependentProperty that defines a user-defined characteristic of an object. The PropertyValue specified by a GeneralShapeDependentProperty is derived from geometry.

NOTE    The GeneralShapeDependentProperty may be used for the purpose of validation of geometric models.

EXAMPLE 1   If a geometry model is exchanged between two partners, the calculation of various properties of the bodies, such as centre of mass, overall surface, or overall volume, is performed by originator and recipient. When comparing these set of values, the existence of deficiencies in the received model can be easily detected.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY GeneralShapeDependentProperty
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  propertyType : PropertyDefinitionSelect;
  propertyValue : PropertyValueSelect;
  unit : OPTIONAL Unit;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

propertyType: the type of characteristic that is specified for an object. The following values shall be used:

  • 'centroid': The PropertyValue identifies the centre point of the mass of a body. The relative position of this point within the body is an invariant datum relative to rotation and translation.;

    EXAMPLE 2   An example, where the use of this GeneralShapeDependentProperty with propertyType 'centroid' is used instead of the object CentreOfMass, is the following: sometimes the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is calculated by some system at some point of time. But there are cases where the information, e.g., the GeneralShapeDependentProperty of a die, is transferred into a following stage, e.g., in order to perform a feasibility check, where there is only a simplified shape representation that does not allow to calculate the exact GeneralShapeDependentProperty. Yet, in this stage the information about the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is needed in order to check whether the transport of a die with a crane is feasible.

  • 'surface area': The PropertyValue specifies the overall surface of the bodies contained in the referenced shape.;
  • 'volume': The PropertyValue specifies the overall volume of the bodies contained in the referenced shape.

propertyValue: the value that is given for a particular characteristic.

unit: the unit in which the GeneralShapeDependentProperty is expressed. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.167 InformationRight   

A InformationRight is a definition of what may or may not be done with an item of information in the sense of legal rights and obligations.

EXAMPLE 1   Copyright is an InformationRight.

EXAMPLE 2   For the purposes of developing a new system, details of government furnished equipment may be made available to a particular project team. The team may copy and use the information internally, but may not pass it on, either to a third part, or to another team, and must destroy the information at the end of the contract.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY InformationRight
  SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (Copyright)));
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  owners : SET[1:?] OF PersonOrOrganizationSelect;
  restriction : OPTIONAL MultiLingualStringSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationRight.

NOTE 1   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the InformationRight is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the InformationRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

owners: the set of Organization or PersonInOrganization objects that own the InformationRight.

restriction: the text that describes any conditions and limitations that apply to the exercise of the right. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

EXAMPLE 3   The description of the right states that copying is permitted within the project team only, whereas the restriction notes the additional constraint that the information must be destroyed at the end of the project.

4.4.168 InformationUsageRight   

An InformationUsageRight is an application an InformationRight to a particular usage context.

NOTE 1   One view of the distinction between an InformationRight and an InformationUsageRight is that the InformationRight represents a standard clause in a contract, whereas an InformationUsageRight represents the fact that the clause is used in a particular contract.

NOTE 2   The context for the usage can be defined through the contract which defines the right, the organization that grants the right, the person or organization which is granted the right, and any dates such as the starting or ending dates for the right. The meaning of each association is identified through the roles of the assignments, and these are defined through reference data.

NOTE 3   The Approval of an InformationUsageRight carries the meaning that the right is granted to all information items in the relevant context, as opposed to the approval of an InformationUsageRightAssignment which is limited to particular items.

NOTE 4   InformationUsageRight provides a mechanism for recording significant rights within a product database. The legal significance of the presence or absence of a right is outside the scope of this part of ISO 10303.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY InformationUsageRight;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  grantsRight : SET[1:?] OF InformationRight;
  owners : SET[1:?] OF PersonOrOrganizationSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationUsageRight.

NOTE 5   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the InformationUsageRight is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationUsageRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the InformationUsageRight. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

grantsRight: the set of InformationRight granted under this usage.

owners: the set of Organization or PersonInOrganization objects that own the InformationUsageRight.

4.4.169 InformationUsageRightAssignment   

A InformationUsageRightAssignment is an assignment of a particular usage right to a set of items.

NOTE 1   If an Approval is applied to this entity, it carries the meaning that the particular set of items is approved for the given usage. This approval generally indicates that the approval is exceptional, for example, where the information belongs to another project, and that project agrees to share some particular items of information. There is a further implication that the set of entities should not be changed once the approval is given.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY InformationUsageRightAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  assignedRight : InformationUsageRight;
  isAssignedTo : SET[1:?] OF InformationUsageRightAssignmentSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the InformationUsageRightAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationUsageRightAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the InformationUsageRightAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: the meaning of the assignment/association. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

assignedRight: the InformationUsageRight which is assigned to the items.

isAssignedTo: the set of InformationUsageRightAssignmentSelect to which the InformationUsageRight applies.

4.4.170 InformationUsageRightRelationship   

An InformationUsageRightRelationship is a relationship of one InformationUsageRight to another.

EXAMPLE 1   Where one InformationUsageRight supersedes another, then the original right is pointed to by the relating attribute, its replacement by the related attribute, and the relationType attribute takes the value supersedes.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY InformationUsageRightRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : InformationUsageRight;
  related : InformationUsageRight;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the InformationUsageRightRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the InformationUsageRightRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship.

relating: one object of InformationUsageRightRelationship that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of InformationUsageRightRelationship that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related InformationUsageRight and the relating InformationUsageRight must be different.

4.4.176 LifeCycleStage   

A LifeCycleStage is a general stage in the product life cycle to which the concerned items belong.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY LifeCycleStage;
  sameAs : SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
UNIQUE
  UR1: sameAs;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

sameAs: the proxies of the LifeCycleStage.

Formal propositions:

UR1: The sameAs shall be unique. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design': The concerned item belongs to the design phase of the life cycle;
  • 'manufacturing': The concerned item belongs to the manufacturing phase of the life cycle;
  • 'support': The concerned item belongs to the support phase of the life cycle;
  • 'recycling': The concerned item belongs to the recycling phase of the life cycle;
  • 'not specific': The object is considered as not specific of any life cycle stage.

4.4.185 MakeFromRelationship   

A MakeFromRelationship is a type of PartViewRelationship that is a relationship between a PartView which provides the definition of a raw material, or of a semi-finished part and a PartView which provides the definition of an object manufactured out of that material, or semi-finished part. The inherited attribute related specifies the raw material or the semi-finished part, and the inherited attribute relating specifies the manufactured part.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY MakeFromRelationship
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  priority : OPTIONAL INTEGER;
  quantity : OPTIONAL ValueWithUnit;
DERIVE
  SELF\PartViewRelationship.relationType : ClassString := 'make from';
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

priority: an integer that ranks the preference for use of the related PartVersion among all instances of MakeFromRelationship that have the same value for the inherited relating attribute. This value is an integer that only has meaning when comparing it with corresponding values for MakeFromRelationship sharing the same relating PartView object. It is a relative ranking value, not an absolute ranking. A lower value indicates a higher preference for the related PartView object, and a higher value indicates a lower preference. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

quantity: the ValueWithUnit that specifies the amount of the related PartVersion that is used to produce the relating PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified; it may be specified when the related PartVersion is a countable material.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'value': value description;

4.4.186 ManufacturingConfiguration   

A ManufacturingConfiguration is an association of a ProductPartEquivalence with a PartOccurrence. Each ManufacturingConfiguration is a SerialConfiguration, a DatedConfiguration, a TimeIntervalConfiguration, or a LotConfiguration.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a ManufacturingConfiguration: Approval, DateTimeString, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ManufacturingConfiguration
  ABSTRACT SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (DatedConfiguration,
                                 LotConfiguration,
                                 SerialConfiguration,
                                 TimeIntervalConfiguration)));
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  concernedOrganizations : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Organization;
  configuredElement : PartOccurrence;
  isSolutionFor : ProductPartEquivalence;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ManufacturingConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the ManufacturingConfiguration is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ManufacturingConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ManufacturingConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

concernedOrganizations: the set of Organization objects in which the ManufacturingConfiguration is valid. The value of this attribute need not be specified. In the case where the concernedOrganizations is not set means that the ManufacturingConfiguration regards any organization that may consider the configuredElement.

configuredElement: a PartOccurrence that is controlled by a ManufacturingConfiguration.

isSolutionFor: the ProductPartEquivalence for which the PartOccurrence is configured.

4.4.188 MatedPartRelationship   

A MatedPartRelationship is a relationship between two MatedPartAssociation objects. This relationship specifies additional information about the mating of two particular items that go into a MatingDefinition. The two MatedPartAssociation objects that are referenced by the MatedPartRelationship shall refer to the same MatingDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY MatedPartRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  matingType : MatingTypeEnum;
  relating : MatedPartAssociation;
  related : MatedPartAssociation;
  matedShapes : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF AssemblyJoint;
  matingMaterials : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF QuantifiedPartOccurrence;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the MatedPartRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the MatedPartRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.


Warning Attr1: The first word of the attribute definition should be lower case. It is:

matingType:

relating: one object of MatedPartAssociation that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of MatedPartAssociation that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

matedShapes: the AssemblyJoint that relates the two ShapeElement objects that form the area of mating contact prior to mating. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

matingMaterials: the set of QuantifiedPartOccurrence objects used as material for the mating. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same MatedPartAssociation.

4.4.193 MatingDefinition   

A MatingDefinition is a type of AssemblyDefinition. It is a view of a PartVersion, defining the physical connection of two or more PartOccurrence objects. It includes technical information about the kind of connection. This information is independent from the hierarchical assembly structure.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY MatingDefinition
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  matingType : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
INVERSE
  matedParts : SET[2:?] OF MatedPartAssociation FOR relating;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

matingType: the kind of mating, that is, how the items shall be mated together. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'bolted joint': Attachment of two or more items that are screwed together using screws, bolt nuts, and washers;
  • 'brazing': Attachment of two or more items established by soldering or brazing;
  • 'clasping': Attachment of two or more items established by using a clamp at one common outer border;
  • 'clinching': Attachment of two or more items established by pressing these items together and stamping texture at the point of contact;
  • 'clipping': Attachment of two or more items established by a clip ( e.g. fixing the inner door panel at the inner door plate);
  • 'doweling': Attachment of two or more items using a pin that is fit into each of each part by pressing;
  • 'flanging': Attachment of two or more items by crimping a projected length of one part over the edge of the other part;
  • 'foam injection': Attachment of two or more items where foam is injected into a cavity to establish the connection;
  • 'gluing': Attachment of two items established by adhesion material;
  • 'laser-welding': Attachment of two or more items that are welded together using a laser technique;
  • 'press fit': Attachment of two or more items obtained by forces resulting from the selected size tolerances;
  • 'riveting': Attachment of two or more items that are riveted together at a certain spot using a rivet;
  • 'sewing': Attachment of two or more items that are sewn together;

    EXAMPLE    Upholstering cloth is sewn together to form a seat pillow.

  • 'spot welding': Attachment of two or more items that are welded together at a certain welding spot;
  • 'stapling': Attachment of two or more items at a certain spot using a nail or a wire stitch to establish the connection;
  • 'welding': Attachment of two or more items by welding together with one weld bead.

matedParts: the set of two or more MatedPartAssociation that reference a MatingDefinition instance as values of their attributes with name relating.

4.4.206 Organization   

An Organization is a group of people involved in a particular business process.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to an Organization: Contract, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Organization;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  deliveryAddress : OPTIONAL Address;
  organizationTypes : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ClassSelect;
  postalAddress : OPTIONAL Address;
  visitorAddress : OPTIONAL Address;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Organization.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

EXAMPLE    The id may be the code assigned to the Organization for a stock market listing, or it may be a department number.

name: the words or set of words by which the Organization is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Organization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Organization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

deliveryAddress: specifies the address where goods are delivered. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

organizationTypes: the type of the Organization. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'company': The organizationTypes specifies that the Organization is a company;
  • 'department': The organizationTypes specifies that the Organization is a department;
  • 'plant': The organizationTypes specifies that the Organization is a plant.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

postalAddress: specifies the address where letter mail is delivered. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

visitorAddress: specifies the address where the organization receives visitors. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.207 OrganizationInContract   

An OrganizationInContract is a mechanism to associate the person who is signing a contract and the organization which the person is signing for, with a Contract.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY OrganizationInContract;
  description : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  contractedOrganization : Organization;
  organizationRole : ClassSelect;
  signedBy : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF DateAndPersonOrganization;
  signedContracts : SET[1:?] OF Contract;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the OrganizationInContract. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the OrganizationInContract. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

contractedOrganization: specifies the organization that participates in the contract.

organizationRole: specifies the function performed by the signing Organization with respect to the contract. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'contractor': The referenced Organization assigns the tasks that are subject of the Contract;
  • 'contractee': The tasks that are subject of the Contract are assigned to the referenced Organization.

signedBy: specifies the set of DateAndPersonOrganization objects representing the personnel that signed the contract on behalf of the contracted organization and the date of the signature. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

signedContracts: specifies the set of Contract objects the OrganizationInContract participates in.

4.4.208 OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment   

An OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment is an object that associates an Organization or a PersonInOrganization with product data. This assignment provides additional information for the associated object. The provision of such data through this assignment has an organizational character whereas some objects require the same kind of data in order to be semantically complete. This assignment shall not be used to associate the corresponding organizational data with an object whose attributes are referencing the organizational data directly. The OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment shall not be used for the purpose of specifying a relationship between two PersonInOrganization objects, e.g., a succession in organizational responsibility. For these purposes, PersonInOrganizationRelationship shall be used.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : ClassSelect;
  assignedPersonOrOrganization : PersonOrOrganizationSelect;
  assignedTo : SET[1:?] OF DateTimePersonOrganizationElementSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: specifies the responsibility of the assigned Person or Organization with respect to the object that it is applied to. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'author': The referenced object has been created by the assigned Person or Organization. The author holds the copyright;
  • 'classification officer': The assigned Person or Organization is formally responsible for the classification of the referenced object;
  • 'creator': The referenced object has been created by the assigned Person or Organization;
  • 'custodian': The assigned Person or Organization is responsible for the existence and integrity of the referenced object;
  • 'customer': The assigned Person or Organization acts as a purchaser or consumer of the referenced object;
  • 'design supplier': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who delivers the data describing the referenced object;

    EXAMPLE    The 'design supplier' may be a design by means of a three-dimensional model or a drawing.

  • 'editor': One or more attributes have been modified by the assigned Person or Organization;
  • 'id owner': The assigned Person or Organization is the one responsible for the designation of an identifier;
  • 'location': The assigned Organization is the place where the referenced object can be found or where it takes place;
  • 'manufacturer': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who produces the actual (physical) object;
  • 'owner': The assigned Person or Organization owns the referenced object, and has final say over its disposition and any changes to it;
  • 'read access’: The assigned Person or Organization neither has the right to modify any attributes of the referenced object, nor to modify, create or delete objects that are attached directly or indirectly to the referenced object;
  • 'supplier': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who delivers the actual (physical) object (e.g., a dealer);
  • 'wholesaler': The assigned Person or Organization is the one who is in the sales chain between the manufacturer and the supplier;
  • 'write access': The assigned Person or Organization has the right to modify the attributes of the referenced object, as well as to modify, create, or delete objects that are attached directly or indirectly to the referenced object.

assignedPersonOrOrganization: specifies the concerned Organization or the PersonInOrganization.

assignedTo: the objects to which the OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment is assigned.

4.4.209 OrganizationRelationship   

An OrganizationRelationship is a relationship between two Organization objects.

EXAMPLE 1   A team belongs to a department which itself belongs to a company. This organizational structure may be built up using the OrganizationRelationship mechanism.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to an OrganizationRelationship: InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY OrganizationRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : Organization;
  related : Organization;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the OrganizationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the OrganizationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'hierarchy': The related Organization is a sub organization of the relating Organization;
  • 'legal succession': The related Organization is the legal successor of the relating Organization;

    NOTE 2   An additional DateTimeAssignmentmay be applied to the OrganizationRelationship in order to specify the time when the succession takes place.

  • 'reorganization': The related Organization is the successor of the relating Organization due to an organizational transfer of responsibility.

    EXAMPLE 2   The name of a department changes due to reorganization.

relating: one object of Organization that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of Organization that is part of the relationship.

NOTE    The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: An Organization shall not be related to itself.

4.4.210 Part   

A Part is a identification of definition of a part. It collects the definitional information of the versions of a part. A Part shall always be categorized as 'piece part', 'product', 'software', 'tool', or 'raw material' using a ClassSelect.

NOTE 1   A Part does not represent an actual physical object of the real world.

NOTE 2   A Part may be either a single piece part, an assembly of arbitrary complexity, a raw material, or a tool.

EXAMPLE 1   In the context of cars, a Part may be the car as a whole, the assembly of the engine, the car body, a fender, the side window glass, grease, or a stamping die.

EXAMPLE 2   In the context of aeroplanes, a Part may be the air plane as a whole, the assembly of the engine, the body of the air plane, a fender, the side window glass, grease, or a stamping die.

NOTE 3   A Part is identified by an organization. The definition of the domain of uniqueness and the mechanism for guaranteeing the uniqueness of Part id are outside the scope of this capability.

NOTE 4   A Part may have zero or more versions. Versions of a Part are represented by the entity PartVersion.

NOTE 5   The following additional data can be assigned to a Part: ActivityMethod, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Part;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  partTypes : SET[1:?] OF ClassSelect;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  versions : SET[1:?] OF PartVersion;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Part.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the Part is known.

NOTE 7   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Part. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Part. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

partTypes: specifies the ClassSelect objects of the Part.

NOTE 8   The partTypes is used to distinguish a part in the Bill of Material (BOM).

NOTE 9   For the attribute id a set of predefined values is specified hereafter. If values other than the proposed ones are used, they should be of general categorizing nature. This kind of categorization ought not to be used to classify names or identifiers of objects, e.g., in order to classify part families; for this purposes ought to be used.

NOTE 10   A Part shall always be categorized as 'piece part', 'product', 'software', 'tool', or 'raw material'.

sameAs: the proxies of the Part. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versions: specifies the PartVersion objects of the Part.

4.4.211 PartOccurrence   

A PartOccurrence is an occurrence of an object in a product structure that is defined either by a PartVersion, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration.

EXAMPLE    In the case of a car, the Item 'wheel' is defined once. Its PartVersion carries all the information necessary to define the wheel (e.g., its shape) independent of its usage. Additionally, there are 5 PartOccurrence objects for this wheel since there are 5 equal wheels used in a car: Front-left, front-right, rear-left, rear-right, and spare wheel. Each of these instances may carry additional information such as placement or function. Each PartOccurrence is a SinglePartOccurrence, a QuantifiedPartOccurrence, a SelectedPartOccurrence, or a SpecifiedPartOccurrence.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartOccurrence: Approval, BreakdownVersion, Certification, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PartOccurrence, PartVersion, BreakdownElement, IndividualPartView, RequirementView, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY PartOccurrence
  ABSTRACT SUPERTYPE OF ((ONEOF (QuantifiedPartOccurrence,
                                 SelectedPartOccurrence,
                                 SinglePartOccurrence,
                                 SpecifiedPartOccurrence)));
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  definition : PartOccurrenceDefinitionSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the PartOccurrence.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PartOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definition: the PartVersion, PartView or the ProductConfiguration that serves as a definition for this particular occurrence. If an appropriate PartVersion or PartView is available, this object shall be used as definition, otherwise a ProductConfiguration shall be referenced.

4.4.216 PartVersion   

A PartVersion is an identification of a version of a part. It serves as the collector of the data characterizing a realizable object in various application contexts.

NOTE 1   A PartVersion is a part that may be produced, consumed, used to produce other PartVersion objects, or offered to the market.

NOTE 2   The collection of defining information may be incomplete, i.e., not all of the PartView objects needed to define a PartVersion are associated with the PartVersion.

NOTE 3   The set of all PartVersion objects of a Part represents the history of the Part within a particular life cycle stage or over its complete life cycle.

NOTE 4   A PartVersion does not have to be referenced by any PartView.

NOTE 5   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartVersion: ActivityMethod, Approval, Certification, Contract, DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PartOccurrence, BreakdownElement, IndividualPartView, RequirementView, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY PartVersion;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  views : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF PartView;
INVERSE
  correspondingProductConfiguration : SET[0:1] OF ProductPartEquivalence FOR associatedPartVersion;
  versionOf : Part FOR versions;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the PartVersion.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

sameAs: the proxies of the PartVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

views: the set of PartView objects that are defined for the PartVersion.

correspondingProductConfiguration: the PartVersion associated with ProductConfiguration

versionOf: the Part with which the PartVersion is associated.

4.4.217 PartVersionRelationship   

A PartVersionRelationship is a relationship between two instances of PartVersion. Unless specified in a specialization of this object, this relationship does not involve inheritance of data between the two related objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartVersionRelationship: Approval, Certification, DateTimeString, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY PartVersionRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : PartVersion;
  related : PartVersion;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PartVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'derivation': The application object defines a deriving relationship where the related PartVersion is based on the relating PartVersion which is an earlier version of the same or of a different Part;
  • 'hierarchy': The application object defines a hierarchical relationship where the related PartVersion is a subordinate version of the relating PartVersion;

    EXAMPLE 1   'Rev. 1.1' and 'rev. 1.2' are subordinates of 'version 1'.

  • 'sequence': The application object defines a version sequence where the relating PartVersion is the preceding version of the related PartVersion that is the following version. For a given PartVersion there shall be at most one PartVersionRelationship of this relationType referring to this PartVersion as ' relating' and at most one PartVersionRelationship of this relationType referring as related.

relating: one object of PartVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of PartVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same PartVersion

4.4.219 PartView   

A PartView is a view of a Part with respect to specific criteria.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a PartView: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, ExternalPropertyDefinition, RequirementVersion, and RequirementView.

                        CollectionDefinition,
                        ConstituentPart,
                        LaminateTable)));
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  additionalContexts : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ViewContext;
  initialContext : ViewContext;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
INVERSE
  viewOf : PartVersion FOR views;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the PartView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PartView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PartView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

additionalContexts: the set of ViewContext objects in which this view of the PartVersion is also relevant. The additionalContexts shall not contain the ViewContext that is referenced as the initialContext. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

initialContext: the ViewContext in which this view of the PartVersion has been designed primarily.

sameAs: the proxies of the PartView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

viewOf: the PartVersion with which the PartView is associated.

4.4.226 Person   

A Person is an individual human being who has some relationship to product data. The Person shall always be identified in the context of one or more organizations.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to an Person: Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Person;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  businessAddress : OPTIONAL Address;
  firstName : OPTIONAL STRING;
  lastName : STRING;
  middleNames : OPTIONAL LIST[1:?] OF STRING;
  prefixTitles : OPTIONAL LIST[1:?] OF STRING;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  suffixTitles : OPTIONAL LIST[1:?] OF STRING;
INVERSE
  associatedOrganizations : SET[1:?] OF PersonInOrganization FOR associatedPerson;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Person. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Person. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Person. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

businessAddress: specifies the location of the office of the Person. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

firstName: the first element of the Person object's list of forenames. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

lastName: the person's name.

middleNames: the person's other forenames. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

prefixTitles: the text that specifies the Person object's social or professional standing and appear before his or her names. The value of this attribute need not be specified. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

EXAMPLE 1   "Mr.", "Ms", "Dr." and combinations are examples of prefixTitles.

sameAs: the proxies of the Person. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

suffixTitles: the text that specifies the Person's social or professional standing and appear after his or her names. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

EXAMPLE 2   "Ph.D." and "Esquire" are examples of suffixTitles.

associatedOrganizations: specifies the Organizations to which the Person belongs to.

4.4.227 PersonInOrganization   

A PersonInOrganization is the specification of a Person in the context of an Organization.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to an PersonInOrganization: Contract, DateTimeString, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY PersonInOrganization;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  associatedOrganization : Organization;
  associatedPerson : Person;
  location : OPTIONAL Address;
  personRole : ClassSelect;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the PersonInOrganization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   The id may be a staff number or a user id in a computer system.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PersonInOrganization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PersonInOrganization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

associatedOrganization: specifies the Organization with which the Person is associated.

associatedPerson: specifies the Person.

location: specifies the relevant address of the PersonInOrganization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

personRole: specifies the relationship between the Person and the Organization.

sameAs: the proxies of the PersonInOrganization. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.228 PersonInOrganizationRelationship   

A PersonInOrganizationRelationship is a mechanism that specifies a relationship between two persons in an organization.

EXAMPLE    The owner of important product data leaves a company and therefore has a successor. This relationship may be built up using the PersonInOrganizationRelationship mechanism.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to an PersonInOrganizationRelationship: InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY PersonInOrganizationRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : PersonInOrganization;
  related : PersonInOrganization;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the PersonInOrganizationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the PersonInOrganizationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'successor': The related PersonInOrganization is the successor of the relating PersonInOrganization;

relating: one object of PersonInOrganization that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of PersonInOrganization that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: An PersonInOrganization shall not be related to itself.
