4.4.245 ProcessOperationDefinition   

A ProcessOperationDefinition is a specification of an activity that may be included in a ProcessPlan. A ProcessOperationDefinition characterizes a manufacturing or control operation.

NOTE 1   ProcessOperationDefinition as well as ProcessOperationOccurrence may be associated with organizational data using, e.g., OrganizationOrPersonInOrganizationAssignment. The reason for having these data available for both types of objects is the requirement to associate ProcessOperationDefinition with organizational data in both a context independent and a context dependent way (the context is a particular ProcessPlan).

NOTE 2   In the case where an instance of ProcessOperationDefinition is associated with, e.g., two Organization objects (e.g., as location), once context independent and once context dependent, the two locations need not be the same, but should be related in a way that the context dependent location should be a specialization of the context independent location e.g., a particular assembly line in a plant).

NOTE 3   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProcessOperationDefinition: DateTimeString, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationDefinition;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  processType : ClassSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProcessOperationDefinition.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the ProcessOperationDefinition is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 5   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the ProcessOperationDefinition. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

processType: the type of the ProcessOperationDefinition.

EXAMPLE    'stamping', 'milling', 'drilling', 'welding', 'casting', and 'painting' are examples for processType.

4.4.246 ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship   

A ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship is a relationship between two ProcessOperationDefinition objects.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : ProcessOperationDefinition;
  related : ProcessOperationDefinition;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'alternative': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition may be used alternatively instead of the relating ProcessOperationDefinition;
  • 'substitution': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition replaces the relating ProcessOperationDefinition;
  • 'version association': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationDefinition is a version of the relating ProcessOperationDefinition. In this case, only the related ProcessOperationDefinition shall specify a versionId;
  • 'version sequence': the application object defines a relationship where the relating ProcessOperationDefinition is the preceding version and the related ProcessOperationDefinition is the following version. In this case, both ProcessOperationDefinition objects shall specify a versionId.

relating: one object of ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of ProcessOperationDefinitionRelationship that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same ProcessOperationDefinition.

4.4.247 ProcessOperationInputOrOutput   

A ProcessOperationInputOrOutput is an input or expected result of a ProcessOperationDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationInputOrOutput;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : ClassSelect;
  concernedShapes : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ShapeElement;
  element : ProcessOperationInputOrOutputSelect;
  operation : ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  placement : OPTIONAL Transformation;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationInputOrOutput. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProcessOperationInputOrOutput. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: the meaning of the assignment/association. Where applicable, the following values shall be used:

  • 'input': the identified element plays the role of an input;
  • 'output': the identified element plays the role of an output.

concernedShapes: the set of ShapeElement objects that are affected by the ProcessOperationOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

element: the element that plays the role of the input or the output for the operation.

operation: the ProcessOperationOccurrence that the ProcessOperationInputOrOutput is associated with.

placement: the geometrical Transformation between the local coordinate system of the element acting as ProcessOperationInputOrOutput, and the reference coordinate system. The reference coordinate system is either the coordinate system of the reference tool, if present for the concerned ProcessOperationOccurrence or, if no reference tool is present, the coordinate system of the ProcessOperationOccurrence itself. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.248 ProcessOperationOccurrence   

A ProcessOperationOccurrence is a usage of a ProcessOperationDefinition in a ProcessPlan. This association states that the ProcessOperationDefinition is part of the ProcessPlan.

NOTE 1   This mechanism enables the reuse of a ProcessOperationDefinition in the context of more than one ProcessPlan.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProcessOperationOccurrence: DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  definedIn : OPTIONAL GeometricCoordinateSpace;
  definition : ProcessOperationDefinition;
  plan : ProcessPlan;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProcessOperationOccurrence.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definedIn: the GeometricCoordinateSpace of the ProcessOperationOccurrence for the case where none of the tools associated by ProcessOperationInputOrOutput plays the role of a reference tool defining the reference coordinate space. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definition: the ProcessOperationDefinition that defines the ProcessOperationOccurrence in a ProcessPlan.

plan: the ProcessPlan to which the ProcessOperationOccurrence is assigning a ProcessOperationDefinition.

4.4.249 ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship   

A ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship is a relationship between two ProcessOperationOccurrence objects.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  related : ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  cycleTime : OPTIONAL Duration;
  waitingTime : OPTIONAL PropertyValue;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProcessOperationOccurrenceRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'decomposition': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationOccurrence is one of the components of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  • 'exclusiveness': the application object defines a relationship where the relating and the related ProcessOperationOccurrence shall not have any overlap in time of execution;
  • 'sequence': the application object defines a relationship where the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence shall be completed before the related ProcessOperationOccurrence starts;
  • 'simultaneity': the application object defines a relationship where the relating and the related ProcessOperationOccurrence objects are considered as occurring during the same time period;

NOTE 1   The criteria for 'simultaneity' and in particular the allowed delay between two ProcessOperationOccurrence objects declared simultaneous, are user-dependent.

NOTE 2   See attribute cycleTime for additional information.

  • 'substitution': the application object defines a relationship where the related ProcessOperationOccurrence replaces of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence.

relating: one object of ProcessOperationOccurrence that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of ProcessOperationOccurrence that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 4   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

cycleTime: the interval of time within which both ProcessOperationOccurrence objects have to take place in order to be declared as simultaneous. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

waitingTime: the time which shall elapse, at least, between the completion of the relating ProcessOperationOccurrence and the start of the related ProcessOperationOccurrence. The referenced shall have a definition that is a Duration.

EXAMPLE    The ProcessOperationOccurrence 'polishing' must not be started less than 2 hours after the ProcessOperationOccurrence 'painting' ended.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same ProcessOperationOccurrence.

4.4.250 ProcessOperationResourceAssignment   

A ProcessOperationResourceAssignment is a mechanism to associate a resource with a ProcessOperationOccurrence.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProcessOperationResourceAssignment: Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProcessOperationResourceAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  assignedResource : ProcessOperationResourceAssignmentSelect;
  assignedTo : ProcessOperationOccurrence;
  placement : OPTIONAL Transformation;
  reason : OPTIONAL MultiLingualStringSelect;
  referenceTool : BOOLEAN;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

assignedResource: the tool that is used to perform the operation.

assignedTo: the ProcessOperationOccurrence with which the resource is associated.

placement: the geometrical Transformation between the local coordinate system of the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment and the reference coordinate system. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   The reference coordinate system is either the coordinate system of the reference tool (if present) for the concerned ProcessOperationDefinition or (if no reference tool is present) the coordinate system of the ProcessOperationDefinition itself. In the case where the value of the attribute referenceTool is 'true', no transformation shall be defined.

reason: the rationale behind the use of the resource for a particular ProcessOperationOccurrence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

referenceTool: specifies whether or not the resource identified by the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment plays the role of the reference tool for the occurrence of an operation. In the case where the value of this attribute is 'true', all geometric transformations within the scope of the ProcessOperationOccurrence are defined with respect to the local coordinate system of the resource identified by the ProcessOperationResourceAssignment. There shall not be more than one resource playing the role of the reference tool for one ProcessOperationOccurrence. In the case where the resource is not represented as a PartView, the value of the attribute referenceTool shall be 'false'.

EXPRESS specification:

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the ProcessPlan is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProcessPlan. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the ProcessPlan. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

producedOutputs: the set of PartVersion objects that are produced by the operations of the ProcessPlan. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.253 ProcessStateRelationship   

A ProcessStateRelationship is a type of PartViewRelationship that is a relationship between two PartView objects where the relating PartView is an in-process-item definition of a particular version of a Part. It characterizes a state of the PartVersion that occurs before the state identified by the related PartView.

NOTE    A ProcessStateRelationship may be used to characterize intermediate states of the PartVersion, if this PartVersion is one of the produced outputs of a ProcessPlan.

EXPRESS specification:

*)

  SELF\PartViewRelationship.relationType : ClassString := 'process state';
END_ENTITY;

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'value': value description;

4.4.254 ProductClass   

A ProductClass is an identification of a set of similar products to be offered to the market. ProductClass objects that are related to each other by a ProductClassRelationship do not inherit any characteristics from each other.

EXAMPLE    The following figure depicts a detail of an example of a structure that is built up by ProductClass and ProductClassRelationship objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProductClass: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProductClass;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  levelType : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  marketSegmentType : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
  marketName : OPTIONAL ClassSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProductClass.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the ProductClass is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

levelType: the level of the ProductClass in a hierarchical structure of ProductClass objects.

EXAMPLE    A high level ProductClass (levelType = 'enterprise') may be used to define all SpecificationCategory and Specification objects for all ProductClass objects of an enterprise with several brands and companies. A second level ProductClass (levelType = 'platform') may be used to group all products that are based on the same technical concept (platform); these products may belong to different brands. A third level ProductClass (levelType = 'car family') may be used to group all products that have a common base and a fixed set of characteristics (specification categories). A fourth level ProductClass (levelType = 'car type') may represent products that are offered to the market; this level of ProductClass may be defined by the marketing department. A set of specifications sufficient to produce the car is associated with its ProductClass. Within this association, a distinction is made between standard characteristics (e.g. number of doors) and options that have to be chosen (e.g., outside colour) or that may be chosen by the customer (e.g., radio).

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

marketSegmentType: the text that identifies a marketing category of the ProductClass. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

marketName: the words or group of words by which the market of the ProductClass is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.255 ProductClassRelationship   

A ProductClassRelationship is a relationship between two ProductClass objects. The meaning of this relationship is specified further by the attribute relationType.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProductClassRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;

WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'derivation': the ProductClassRelationship defines a relationship where the related ProductClass is derived from the relating ProductClass;
  • 'hierarchy': the ProductClassRelationship defines a relationship where the relating ProductClass is on a higher level in the hierarchy of ProductClass objects than the related ProductClass;
  • 'substitution': the ProductClassRelationship defines a relationship where the related ProductClass replaces the relating ProductClass;
  • 'version sequence': the ProductClassRelationship defines a relationship where the relating ProductClass is the preceding version and the related ProductClass is the following version.

relating: one object of ProductClass that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

4.4.256 ProductConfiguration   

A ProductConfiguration is a manufacturable object, or expected as so. A ProductConfiguration is defined with respect to the ProductClass it is a member of.

NOTE 1   The kind of product that is to be manufactured from the data of the ProductConfiguration, is the kind of product that the memberOf identifies a class of.

NOTE 2   The intent of ProductConfiguration is the identification of one manufacturable object whereas the intent of ProductClass is the gathering of products with similar characteristics.

EXAMPLE 1   A ProductConfiguration that is associated with a ProductClass that identifies a family of diesel engines is intended to lead to the manufacture of a particular case of diesel engine, and the ProductConfiguration that is associated with a ProductClass that identifies a car family will lead to the manufacture of a car.

NOTE 3   The entity ProductConfiguration corresponds to the concept of configuration item defined, in some configuration management standards, as an item subject to configuration management.

EXAMPLE 2   A ProductConfiguration may represent a component of a contracted product, onto which severe safety rules apply and for which configuration management is therefore rigorously applied.

NOTE 4   A ProductConfiguration may identify a variation of a ProductClass, an entire ProductClass, or some portion thereof.

NOTE 5   A ProductConfiguration can be established prior to the existence of a corresponding product.

For a ProductConfiguration one or more additional Specification objects may be specified. In this case they enhance the characterization provided for the associated ProductClass.

NOTE 6   The actual set of Specification objects for a ProductConfiguration are obtained by the union of definingSpecifications and of the Specification objects related to the associatedProductClass through a ClassSpecificationAssociation or a ClassConditionAssociation with associationType 'identification' or 'non replaceable standard'.

NOTE 7   The specification of a ProductConfiguration may be incomplete: there may not be in definingSpecifications any instance of Specification for some SpecificationCategory declared as mandatory for the associatedProductClass. For these SpecificationCategory objects any Specification available in the context of the associatedProductClass is considered as valid for the manufacturing of the product characterized by the considered ClassSpecificationAssociation.

EXAMPLE 3   If the colour is not specified for a given car family, the vehicle resulting from the realization of a ProductConfiguration associated to the ProductClass representing the car family may be without paint or painted in any available colour.

NOTE 8   The following additional data can be assigned to a ProductConfiguration: ActivityMethod, Approval, BreakdownVersion, Contract, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, Project, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProductConfiguration;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  definingSpecifications : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Specification;
  memberOf : ProductClass;
INVERSE
  correspondingPartVersion : SET[0:1] OF ProductPartEquivalence FOR associatedProductConfiguration;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the ProductConfiguration.

NOTE 9   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the ProductConfiguration is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 10   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 11   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProductConfiguration. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definingSpecifications: the set of Specification objects necessary to discriminate the ClassSpecificationAssociation within its ProductClass. Each definingSpecifications shall be associated with a ProductClass by a ClassSpecificationAssociation with associationType not equal 'part usage'. The associated ProductClass shall be either the associated ProductClass of the ProductConfiguration or any higher level ProductClass related directly or indirectly by a ProductClassRelationship with a relationType 'hierarchy'. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

memberOf: the ProductClass that a ProductConfiguration belongs to.

correspondingPartVersion: the ProductPartEquivalence that associates this ProductConfiguration with a PartVersion.

4.4.257 ProductConfigurationRelationship   

A ProductConfigurationRelationship is a relationship between two ProductConfiguration objects. The meaning of this relationship is specified further by the attribute relationType.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProductConfigurationRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : ProductConfiguration;
  related : ProductConfiguration;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProductConfigurationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProductConfigurationRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: specifies the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'hierarchy': the ProductConfigurationRelationship defines a relationship where the relating ProductConfiguration is on a higher level in the hierarchy of ProductConfiguration objects than the related ProductConfiguration;
  • 'version sequence': the ProductConfigurationRelationship defines a relationship where the relating ProductConfiguration is the preceding version and the related ProductConfiguration is the following version.

relating: one object of ProductConfiguration that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of ProductConfiguration that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same ProductConfiguration.

4.4.258 ProductPartEquivalence   

A ProductPartEquivalence is a mechanism to associate an PartVersion with its corresponding ProductConfiguration. It specifies the explicit design that corresponds to the ProductConfiguration. The ProductPartEquivalence represents the statement that, in all definition contexts, the PartVersion is a valid way to implement the ProductConfiguration.

NOTE    The ProductPartEquivalence might not be valid for other PartVersion objects.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ProductPartEquivalence;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  associatedPartVersion : PartVersion;
  associatedProductConfiguration : ProductConfiguration;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ProductPartEquivalence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the ProductPartEquivalence. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

associatedPartVersion: the PartVersion that identifies a part which is a valid implementation for the ProductConfiguration, i.e. meets the requirements specified by the ProductConfiguration.

associatedProductConfiguration: the ProductConfiguration that represents the requirements for which a PartVersion as solution is designated.

4.4.275 QuantifiedPartOccurrence   

A QuantifiedPartOccurrence is the identification of the quantified occurrence of an object that is defined either as a PartOccurrence, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration.

EXAMPLE 1   Radiator liquid or engine oil are examples for QuantifiedPartOccurrence objects.

EXAMPLE 2   In a TechnicalSolution for the front left brake a certain screw is used four times.

A QuantifiedPartOccurrence is a type of PartOccurrence.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY QuantifiedPartOccurrence
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  quantity : NumericalValue;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

quantity: a NumericalValue specifying the quantity of occurrences. If the quantity can not be expressed as a particular value, the concept of SelectedPartOccurrence shall be used instead to represent this instance.

NOTE    The quantity may be specified as a count measure, as a mass measure, as a length measure, as an area measure, or as a volume measure.

4.4.281 Requirement   

A Requirement is an essential characteristic, condition, or capability that shall be met or exceeded by a system or a component to satisfy a contract, standard, specification, or other formally imposed document.

NOTE 1   The term "requirement" is used here in the sense that term is used in systems engineering and similar industrial domains.

NOTE 2   There may be many versions of a Requirement through RequirementVersion. There may also be more than one domain-specific view of a given RequirementVersion (using the RequirementView entity). The Requirement entity is simply a placeholder for holding a unique requirement. Most associations and properties could be defined at the Requirement, RequirementVersion or RequirementView level - that is in the context of a domain.

EXAMPLE    A requirement may be identified as "NOx emissions requirement", and uniquely identified as "Req2".

NOTE 3   Systems engineering tools and organizations may use differing identification mechanisms. Multiple identifiers may be managed in Requirement using the id attribute.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Requirement;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  versions : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF RequirementVersion;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Requirement.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the Requirement is known.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

sameAs: the proxies of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versions: the versions of the Requirement. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.282 RequirementAssignment   

A RequirementAssignment is used to relate a Requirement (via RequirementVersion or RequirementView) to data types representing the items (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) which are affected by the requirement.

EXAMPLE    A requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP" could be assigned to the data types which are used to represent the vehicle's engine.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  assignedRequirement : RequirementVersionOrViewSelect;
  assignedTo : RequirementAssignmentSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementAssignment.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

assignedRequirement: the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView which is assigned.

assignedTo: the item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) which has the requirement assigned to it.

4.4.283 RequirementCollectionRelationship   

A RequirementCollectionRelationship is a type of RequirementViewRelationship. It identifies a collection relationship that is used to relate a parent (collection) requirement to its member requirements. This provides a method for collecting together a set of requirements and treating them as a single requirement, whilst still being able to refer to individual requirements.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementCollectionRelationship
  SUBTYPE OF ();
DERIVE
  SELF\RequirementViewRelationship.relationType : ClassString := 'collection';
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class name shall be used:

  • 'collection': the relationType specifies that the RequirementViewRelationship is a collection;

4.4.284 RequirementDecompositionRelationship   

A RequirementDecompositionRelationship is a type of RequirementCollectionRelationship. It identifies a decomposition relationship. This provides a method to represent a decomposition of requirements.

EXPRESS specification:

*)

4.4.285 RequirementSatisfactionAssertion   

A RequirementSatisfactionAssertion is a relationship between an item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) and a requirement (via RequirementVersion or the RequirementView), asserting that the item satisfies the identified requirement.

EXAMPLE    A data type used to represent a vehicle's engine with a power output of 160BHP could be asserted to satisfy a requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP".

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementSatisfactionAssertion;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  assertedBy : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF DateAndPersonOrganization;
  relatedAssignment : OPTIONAL RequirementAssignment;
  satisfiedBy : RequirementAssignmentSelect;
  satisfiedRequirement : RequirementVersionOrViewSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

assertedBy: the date and the Organization or the PersonInOrganization (via DateAndPersonOrganization) that has asserted the requirement satisfaction. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relatedAssignment: the RequirementAssignment that is satisfied by the RequirementSatisfactionAssertion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

satisfiedBy: the item (specified in RequirementAssignmentSelect) that satisfies the requirement.

satisfiedRequirement: the requirement (via the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView) that is satisfied.

4.4.286 RequirementSequenceRelationship

EXPRESS specification:

*)

4.4.287 RequirementSourceAssociation   

A RequirementSourceAssociation is a relationship between a requirement (via the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView) and the data types representing the source (specified in RequirementSourceSelect) of the requirement.

EXAMPLE    The source of the requirement "the vehicle shall have a maximum power output of at least 150BHP" could be a document representing the findings of a market survey of sports car buyers.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementSourceAssociation;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  source : RequirementSourceSelect;
  sourcedRequirement : RequirementVersionOrViewSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementSourceAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementSourceAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementSourceAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

sameAs: the proxies of the RequirementSourceAssociation. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

source: the item which is the source (specified in RequirementSourceSelect) of the requirement.

sourcedRequirement: the RequirementVersion or the RequirementView which is to be related to its source.

4.4.288 RequirementTracingRelationship   

A RequirementTracingRelationship is a type of RequirementViewRelationship. It identifies a tracing relationship.

EXAMPLE    A requirement on the performance of a catalytic converter in a car may be traced from a more general emissions requirement.

A requirement may trace to many other requirements and vice versa - this is achieved by creating multiple instances of the tracing relationship entity.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementTracingRelationship
  SUBTYPE OF ();
DERIVE
  SELF\RequirementViewRelationship.relationType : ClassString := 'tracing';
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class name shall be used:

  • 'tracing': the relationType specifies that the RequirementViewRelationship is a tracing relationship;

4.4.289 RequirementVersion   


Warning Ent3: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementVersion. Check that the description starts with " A or an RequirementVersion is "
A RequirementVersion identifies a particular version of a requirement.

NOTE    This entity is used to record different versions of a requirement. In this case, the word "version" implies "revision" - that is a particular release of a requirement.

EXAMPLE    A given requirement might have versions 1.0, 1.1, 1.2 and 2.0.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementVersion;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
  views : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF RequirementView;
INVERSE
  versionOf : Requirement FOR versions;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementVersion.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

sameAs: the proxies of the RequirementVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

views: the views of the RequirementVersion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionOf: the Requirement that the RequirementVersion is a version of.

4.4.290 RequirementVersionRelationship   

A RequirementVersionRelationship is a type of relationship that is used to relate previous version (related) of a requirement to the version that replaces it (relating).

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementVersionRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : RequirementVersion;
  related : RequirementVersion;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementVersionRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class name shall be used:

  • 'sequence': the relationType specifies that the RequirementVersionRelationship is a sequence;

relating: one object of RequirementVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   This object represent the new version of a requirement (via RequirementVersion)

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of RequirementVersion that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 3   This object represent the old version of a requirement (via RequirementVersion)

NOTE 4   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related object and the relating object must not be the same RequirementVersion.

4.4.291 RequirementView   


Warning Ent3: managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.RequirementView. Check that the description starts with " A or an RequirementView is "
A RequirementView provides a view of a requirement version relevant for one or more application domains. This view collects requirement data for specific engineering purposes.

EXAMPLE    An engineer may have responsibility for collecting all requirements associated with the cooling of an engine - covering engine block, tubing, water pump, electric fan.

Some requirements in a RequirementView might impact on different disciplines. Multiple RequirementView instances may be used to present different views of a given requirement for each discipline.

The definition of the requirement is represented by a set of definitional properties referenced from RequirementView.definitionalRepresentations. If more than one definitional property is provided each property shall be equivalent. Any other property that is associated with the RequirementView is assumed to be a non-defining property, such as an annotation etc.

EXAMPLE    The requirement that the weight should be less than 4 Kgs can be represented by a string representation "weight must be 4Kg" and a numeric representation "4Kg" specified as a value with units.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RequirementView;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  additionalContexts : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ViewContext;
  definitionalRepresentations : SET[1:?] OF PropertyValue;
  initialContext : ViewContext;
  sameAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ProxySelect;
INVERSE
  viewOf : RequirementVersion FOR views;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RequirementView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RequirementView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RequirementView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

additionalContexts: the set of ViewContext objects in which this view of the RequirementVersion is also relevant. The additionalContexts shall not contain the ViewContext that is referenced as the initialContext. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

definitionalRepresentations: the properties that define the requirement.

initialContext: the ViewContext in which this view of the RequirementVersion has been designed primarily.

sameAs: the proxies of the RequirementView. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

viewOf: the RequirementVersion of which the RequirementView provides a characterization.

4.4.293 RetentionPeriod   

A RetentionPeriod is the definition of a period of time that product data needs to be maintained due to organizational policy or legal requirements.

NOTE    The following additional data can be assigned to a RetentionPeriod: InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY RetentionPeriod;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  assignedTo : SET[1:?] OF GeneralOrganizationalDataSelect;
  earliestEnd : PeriodOrDateSelect;
  latestEnd : PeriodOrDateSelect;
  start : EventOrDateSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the RetentionPeriod. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the RetentionPeriod. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the RetentionPeriod. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

assignedTo: the objects whose existence is controlled by the RetentionPeriod.

NOTE    The master document is the one for which earliestEnd and latestEnd are the same.

earliestEnd: the point in time after which any object the RetentionPeriod is applied to may be deleted or destroyed

NOTE    In this context deletion or destruction applies to all subordinate objects that are not referenced by other objects.

latestEnd: the point in time before which any objects that the RetentionPeriod is applied to shall be deleted or destroyed.

NOTE    In this context deletion or destruction applies to all subordinate objects that are not used by other objects.

start: the point in time at which the RetentionPeriod starts.

4.4.294 SameTimeMachiningRelationship   

A SameTimeMachiningRelationship is a type of PartOccurrenceRelationship relationship between two PartOccurrence objects that specifies that those two objects shall be manufactured together within the same ProcessOperationOccurrence.

Figure 3 —   illustration of SameTimeMachiningRelationship

*)

In the case where the placement is realized by a TemplateInstance the scale factor of that TemplateInstance shall be omitted or set to 1. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable, the following class names shall be used:

  • 'value': value description;

4.4.297 SelectedPartOccurrence   

A SelectedPartOccurrence is a type of PartOccurrence that is the identification of the occurrence of an object that is either defined as a PartVersion, PartView or as a ProductConfiguration and whose quantity depends on certain constraints.

EXAMPLE 1   In a BOM where the exact amount of grease or glue can usually not be specified as a quantity, the specification of this grease or glue are examples for SelectedPartOccurrence objects.

EXAMPLE 2   To minimize the concentricity error of a wheel, weights are attached to the rim; this set of weights is a SelectedPartOccurrence. The quantity as well as the position of these weights depends on the concentricity behaviour of each particular wheel as manufactured and tested.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SelectedPartOccurrence
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  criterion : MultiLingualStringSelect;
  quantity : ValueWithUnit;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

criterion: the constraint that has to be evaluated for the SelectedPartOccurrence.

EXAMPLE 3   'as required for balance' and 'as required for lubrication' are examples for a criterion.

quantity: the quantity of the part, tool or raw material foreseen as SelectedPartOccurrence. The quantity shall be of type ValueLimit or ValueRange.

NOTE    If the quantity is to be specified as a minimum and/or a maximum, then ValueLimit or ValueRange may be used.

EXAMPLE 4   The quantity of engine oil used in a car may be in the range of 3.7 to 3.9 litres. This is expressed using ValueRange as the quantity.

4.4.298 SerialConfiguration   

A SerialConfiguration is a type of ManufacturingConfiguration that applies onwards from a given serial number of the product that is considered within the object referred to as isSolutionFor.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SerialConfiguration
  SUBTYPE OF ();
  endNumber : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  startNumber : IdentifierSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

endNumber: the serial number of that instance of the product that is the last instance for which the SerialConfiguration applies. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    If the endNumber is not specified, it is not foreseen that the SerialConfiguration ceases to be valid; i.e., the SerialConfiguration is expected to apply to all serial numbers greater than the serial start number for the product for whose characteristics the SerialConfiguration identifies a solution.

startNumber: the serial number of that instance of the product that is the first instance for which the SerialConfiguration applies.

4.4.306 SizeProperty   

A SizeProperty is the specification of the size of a File or of a DocumentDefinition object. At least one of the optional attributes shall be specified for each instance of this object. In the case where a SizeProperty is referred by a DocumentDefinition, the size information is the sum of the sizes of all individual objects that are collected by this object, whereas in the case it is referred by a File, the size information is the one of the individual objects that is referenced.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SizeProperty;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  fileSize : OPTIONAL ValueWithUnit;
  pageCount : OPTIONAL ValueWithUnit;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SizeProperty. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

fileSize: the ValueWithUnit that represents the size of a digitally stored document. The value of this attribute need not be specified. The fileSize shall only be applied in cases where the SizeProperty is referred by a DigitalDocumentDefinition or a File.

EXAMPLE 1   '15021 Bytes' and 'less than 500 Bytes' are examples for a fileSize.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

pageCount: the number of pages of the application object the SizeProperty is referred by. The value of this attribute need not be specified. The pageCount shall only be used in cases where the SizeProperty is referred by a Hardcopy or a PhysicalDocumentDefinition.

EXAMPLE 2   '42 pages' and 'more than 1 page' are examples of a pageCount.

The value of this attribute need not be specified.

4.4.308 Specification   

A Specification is a characteristic of a product. A Specification discriminates one product from other members of the same ProductClass. A Specification refers to a SpecificationCategory that completes the semantics of the Specification.

NOTE 1   A Specification may be a characteristic of the members of more than one ProductClass using BreakdownAssignment objects.

NOTE 2   A Specification in combination with a Configuration may be used to define under which conditions a Part is used in combination with a ProductClass.

EXAMPLE    'coupe', 'hatch back', or 'sedan' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'car body'. 'radio 1 with CD player' and 'radio 2 without CD player' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'radio equipment'. 'disk brake' and 'drum brake' are examples for specifications belonging to the SpecificationCategory of type 'braking system'.

NOTE 3   The following additional data can be assigned to a Specification: Approval, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, InformationUsageRight, PropertyValue, PropertyDefinition, and ExternalPropertyDefinition.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY Specification;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  category : SpecificationCategory;
  package : BOOLEAN;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the Specification.

NOTE 4   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the Specification is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 5   This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 6   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1

classifiedAs: the classifications of the Specification. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

category: the SpecificationCategory that completes the semantics of the Specification.

package: specifies whether this Specification represents a package of Specification objects or not. Such a Specification combines those Specification objects that shall be offered to the market as a set. In the case where package is 'true', there shall be exactly one SpecificationInclusion per ProductClass considered, that refers to this Specification by its attribute ifCondition. The Specification objects that are members of the package, shall be specified in the attribute includedSpecification of the SpecificationInclusion.

NOTE 7   Commercial packages may be defined by the marketing department.

NOTE 8   Usually the members of a package belong to distinct SpecificationCategory objects.

EXAMPLE    A sports package contains sports seats, a special steering wheel, special tyres and wheels. A winter package contains heated front seats, heated windshield washers, heated exterior mirrors, and special tyres.

4.4.309 SpecificationCategory   

A SpecificationCategory is a definition of a set of Specification objects serving the same purpose.

EXAMPLE 1   The category 'kind of drive' for the Specification objects 'front wheel drive' and 'rear wheel drive' or the category 'level of equipment' for the Specification objects 'standard', 'comfortable', and 'luxurious' are examples for SpecificationCategory objects.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a SpecificationCategory: Approval, DateTimeString, Document, DocumentVersion, DocumentDefinition, File, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SpecificationCategory;
  id : IdentifierSelect;
  description : DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  implicitExclusiveCondition : BOOLEAN;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the SpecificationCategory.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationCategory.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the SpecificationCategory. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

implicitExclusiveCondition: specifies whether the Specification objects within the SpecificationCategory are mutually exclusive for the production of one particular product. A value of 'true' indicates that the referenced objects are mutually exclusive for the production of the particular product.

EXAMPLE 2   'safety equipment' is an example for a non mutually exclusive SpecificationCategory if, e.g., ABS and air bag are Specification objects in this category. 'engine' is an example for a SpecificationCategory with an implicitExclusiveCondition since usually only one engine can be mounted for power supply.

NOTE 3   More complex conditions can be handled using SpecificationExpression objects.

4.4.310 SpecificationCategoryHierarchy   

A SpecificationCategoryHierarchy is a used to build up hierarchical structures of SpecificationCategory objects.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SpecificationCategoryHierarchy;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  subCategory : SpecificationCategory;
  superCategory : SpecificationCategory;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationCategoryHierarchy. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the SpecificationCategoryHierarchy. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

subCategory: the lower level of SpecificationCategory in SpecificationCategoryHierarchy.

superCategory: the higher level of SpecificationCategory in SpecificationCategoryHierarchy.

4.4.311 SpecificationExpression   

A SpecificationExpression is a combination of Specification objects formed by Boolean operations.

NOTE 1   The following additional data can be assigned to a SpecificationExpression: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SpecificationExpression;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  operands : SET[1:?] OF SpecificationOperandSelect;
  theOperation : SpecificationExpressionOperationEnum;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the SpecificationExpression. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationExpression. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the SpecificationExpression. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

operands: the operands of the Boolean operation that are either Specification objects or other SpecificationExpression objects. In case theOperation is 'not' there shall be exactly one operand.

theOperation: the kind of Boolean operation. The following kinds of operations are permitted:

  • 'and': all of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • 'or': a subset or all of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • 'oneof': exactly one of the identified Specification objects shall be used;
  • not': The identified Specification shall not be used. 'not' is an unary operation.

4.4.312 SpecificationInclusion   

A SpecificationInclusion is a representation of the statement that specifies that the application of a Specification or of a SpecificationExpression implies the inclusion of an additional Specification or SpecificationExpression.

EXAMPLE    The source of such a completion may be a customer order.

NOTE 1   The SpecificationInclusion is intended to complete the set of Specification objects for a BreakdownAssignment in order to enable the manufacturing of the product on the basis of an initial set of Specification objects defined.

NOTE 2   The following additional data can be assigned to a SpecificationInclusion: Approval, DateTimeString, Effectivity, and InformationUsageRight.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY SpecificationInclusion;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  ifCondition : SpecificationOperandSelect;
  includedSpecification : SpecificationOperandSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the SpecificationInclusion. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

ifCondition: the Specification or the SpecificationExpression that serves as the condition for the inclusion.

includedSpecification: the Specification or the SpecificationExpression objects that are to be included. The includedSpecification shall not reference a SpecificationExpression with an operation of type 'or' or 'oneof', except for negating expressions, i.e., as participants in an expression preceded by a 'not' operator. Expressions of operator 'not' shall not be nested within one another.

In the case where more than one Specification is to be included a SpecificationExpression of type 'and' shall be used.

NOTE 4   In the case where the includedSpecification is a 'not' expression, the object actually defines an exclusion.

4.4.330 TimeInterval   

A TimeInterval is the specification of a unit of time.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY TimeInterval;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  name : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  endDefinition : PeriodOrDateSelect;
  startDefinition : EventOrDateSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the TimeInterval. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

name: the words or set of words by which the TimeInterval is known. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multiple names in different contexts as well as multi linguism.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the TimeInterval. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

endDefinition: defines the end of the TimeInterval, either by referring to a bound, or specifying the extend of the TimeInterval by a Duration. If the endDefinition refers to an Event or DateTimeString, this particular bound of the resulting interval is excluded from it.

startDefinition: defines the beginning of the TimeInterval. The bound specified by the startDefinition is included in the resulting interval.

4.4.331 TimeIntervalAssignment   

A TimeIntervalAssignment is an association of an TimeInterval with some product data. The TimeIntervalAssignment shall neither be used to convey effectivity information, i.e., information concerning valid use of product data, nor to convey retention information, nor duration information.

NOTE    Such information is conveyed using Effectivity, RetentionPeriod, and Duration respectively.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY TimeIntervalAssignment;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  role : ClassSelect;
  assignedTimeInterval : TimeInterval;
  assignedTo : SET[1:?] OF GeneralOrganizationalDataSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the TimeIntervalAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE    This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the TimeIntervalAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the TimeIntervalAssignment. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

role: the meaning of the assignment/association. Where applicable, the following values shall be used:

  • 'installation': The assignment specifies that the object referenced as assignedTo was mounted in a product during the given interval of time;

assignedTimeInterval: specifies the TimeInterval that is associated with the product data.

assignedTo: specifies the set of objects of product data with which the TimeIntervalAssignment is assigned.

4.4.346 ViewContext   

A ViewContext is a grouping of an application domain and a life cycle stage. It identifies a universe of discourse suitable for the description of parts.

NOTE    Requirements and vocabularies vary among the industrial activity fields. This entity intends to identify such domains.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY ViewContext;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  applicationDomain : ApplicationDomainSelect;
  lifeCycleStage : LifeCycleStageSelect;
UNIQUE
  UR1: applicationDomain, lifeCycleStage;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the ViewContext. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

applicationDomain: the identification of the applications for which an object may be relevant. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'assembly study': The object may be relevant for an assembly study;
  • 'digital mock-up': The object may be relevant for digital mock-up;
  • 'electrical design': The object may be relevant for the electrical design;
  • 'mechanical design': The object may be relevant for the mechanical design;
  • 'preliminary design': The object may be relevant for the preliminary design;
  • 'process planning': The object may be relevant for the process planning;
  • 'product support': The object may be relevant for the product support;
  • 'not specific': The object is considered as not specific of any application domain.

lifeCycleStage: the general stage in the product life cycle to which the concerned items belong. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design': The concerned item belongs to the design phase of the life cycle;
  • 'manufacturing': The concerned item belongs to the manufacturing phase of the life cycle;
  • 'support': The concerned item belongs to the support phase of the life cycle;
  • 'recycling': The concerned item belongs to the recycling phase of the life cycle;
  • 'not specific': The object is considered as not specific of any life cycle stage.

Formal propositions:

UR1: The combination of the applicationDomain and the lifeCycleStage shall be unique.

4.4.347 WorkOrder   

A WorkOrder is an authorization for one or more Activity objects to be performed.

NOTE 1   One or more means that it is controlling the main activity and any sub-activity related to the activity by ActivityRelationship with relationType of 'decomposition'.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY WorkOrder;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  orderType : ClassSelect;
  inResponseTo : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF WorkRequest;
  isControlling : SET[1:?] OF Activity;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the WorkOrder. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the WorkOrder. The value of this attribute need not be specified.


Warning Ent7: bold text "clause for fundamental concepts" found in definition of express identifier "managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkOrder.versionId" If an express identifier, consider tagging as <express_ref>.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the WorkOrder. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for fundamental concepts

classifiedAs: the classifications of the WorkOrder. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

orderType: the orderType specifies the kind of the WorkOrder. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'design deviation permit': An authorization for a deviation from the approved design data;
  • 'design release': An authorization for the design of a product or of an item or to create a bill of material;
  • 'management resolution': An authorization by a committee, such as the board of directors, to design or change an item;
  • 'manufacturing release': An authorization for the manufacturing process of a product or of an item;
  • 'production deviation permit': An authorization for a deviation from the approved manufacturing process.

inResponseTo: one or many instances of WorkRequest that define the expected WorkOrder. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

isControlling: the Activity objects that are controlled by this particular WorkOrder

4.4.348 WorkRequest   

A WorkRequest is a solicitation for some work to be done.

NOTE 1   These requests may not be acted upon depending on the authorization granted to the request or its associated WorkOrder.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY WorkRequest;
  id : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  versionId : OPTIONAL IdentifierSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  requestType : ClassSelect;
  notifiedPersons : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF DateAndPersonOrganization;
  requestor : DateAndPersonOrganization;
  scopes : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF ActivityAssignmentSelect;
  status : ClassSelect;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

id: the identifier or set of identifiers for the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 2   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in Clause 4.1.

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.


Warning Ent7: bold text "clause for fundamental concepts" found in definition of express identifier "managed_model_based_3d_engineering_bom.WorkRequest.versionId" If an express identifier, consider tagging as <express_ref>.

versionId: the identification or set of identifications of a particular version of the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

NOTE 3   This attribute supports multi identification in different contexts as described in clause for fundamental concepts

classifiedAs: the classifications of the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

requestType: the intention of the WorkRequest. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'change of standard': A request to translate a change to a standard into action;
  • 'cost reduction': A request aimed at reducing the engineering and manufacturing costs of an item;
  • 'customer rejection': A request resulting from a rejection by a customer;
  • 'customer request': A request for an activity that is necessary to solve the request of a customer;
  • 'durability improvement': A request aimed at extending the life time of an item;
  • 'government regulation': A request resulting from legal requirements;
  • 'procurement alignment': A request to adjust the purchasing process of different items;
  • 'production alignment': A request to adjust the manufacturing process of different items;
  • 'production relief': A request aimed at achieving a simpler assembly and production process;
  • 'production requirement': A request for an activity that is necessary from a production point of view;
  • 'quality improvement': A request aimed at increasing the quality of an item;
  • 'security reason': A request for an activity that is necessary from a security point of view;
  • 'standardization': A request to unify variants of an item;
  • 'supplier request': A request for an activity necessary to solve the request of a supplier;
  • 'technical improvement': A request aimed at improving the technical aspects of an item;
  • 'tool improvement': A request aimed at increasing the useful life of a tool.

notifiedPersons: the personnel that shall be informed about the WorkRequest and the date when the personnel or organization shall be informed. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

requestor: the person or organization who issued the WorkRequest and the date when this person or organization issued the WorkRequest.

scopes: the objects that are subject to the WorkRequest. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

status: the text that provides a user interpretable designation for the level of completion of the study and resolution of the WorkRequest.

EXAMPLE 1   The designations 'drafted', 'issued', 'deferred', 'proposed', 'in-work', 'completed', 'resolved', 'cancelled', and 'rejected' are examples of request status.

4.4.349 WorkRequestRelationship   

A WorkRequestRelationship is a relationship between two WorkRequest objects.

EXPRESS specification:

*)
ENTITY WorkRequestRelationship;
  description : OPTIONAL DescriptorSelect;
  classifiedAs : OPTIONAL SET[1:?] OF Classification;
  relationType : ClassSelect;
  relating : WorkRequest;
  related : WorkRequest;
WHERE
  WR1: relating :<>: related;
END_ENTITY;
(*

Attribute definitions:

description: the text or the set of texts that provide further information about the WorkRequestRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

classifiedAs: the classifications of the WorkRequestRelationship. The value of this attribute need not be specified.

relationType: the meaning of the relationship. Where applicable the following values shall be used:

  • 'dependency': The related WorkRequest is dependent on the relating WorkRequest.

relating: one object of WorkRequest that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 1   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

related: the other object of WorkRequest that is part of the relationship.

NOTE 2   The semantics of this attribute are defined by the attribute relationType.

Formal propositions:

WR1: the related WorkRequestRelationship and the relating WorkRequestRelationship must be different.
